  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is typically defined as the process of concealing the origin of illegally obtained money, usually through a series of complex transactions. Legal definitions can vary by jurisdiction, but generally include:\n\n1. Core elements:\n- Disguising the source of illegally obtained funds\n- Making \"dirty\" money appear \"clean\" and legitimate\n- Transforming proceeds from criminal activities into seemingly legal assets\n\n2. Common statutory components:\n- Intentional concealment of financial transactions\n- Transferring funds to hide criminal origins\n- Engaging in financial activities to mask illegal proceeds\n\n3. Key stages typically recognized:\n- Placement (introducing illegal funds into financial system)\n- Layering (creating complex transactions to obscure origin)\n- Integration (reintroducing funds as seemingly legitimate income)\n\n4. Specific activities often considered money laundering:\n- Structuring bank deposits\n- Using shell companies\n- International wire transfers\n- Complex financial transactions\n- Converting cash into other assets\n\n5. Typical predicate crimes:\n- Drug trafficking\n- Fraud\n- Corruption\n- Organized crime\n- Terrorism financing\n\nEach jurisdiction has specific legal nuances, so precise definitions can differ between countries and legal systems.",
